INSERT INTO `text` VALUES (1,_binary '<strong>MediaWiki has been installed.</strong>\n\nConsult the [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Help:Contents User\'s Guide] for information on using the wiki software.\n\n== Getting started ==\n* [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Manual:Configuration_settings Configuration settings list]\n* [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Manual:FAQ MediaWiki FAQ]\n* [https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-announce MediaWiki release mailing list]\n* [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Localisation#Translation_resources Localise MediaWiki for your language]\n* [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Manual:Combating_spam Learn how to combat spam on your wiki]',_binary 'utf-8'),(2,_binary 'Welcome to the CUUASS Wiki!\n\n==Purpose of this Wiki==\nA major problem that many student societies (in particular Engineering societies) face is the fact that members generally don\'t stay longer than four years. This makes it very difficult to conserve knowledge. The purpose of this wiki is for CUUASS\'s members (and anybody else who is interested in developing and manufacturing autonomous drones for that matter) to document their knowledge (e.g. manufacturing techniques, usage of various non-self-explanatory tools, documentation of algorithms, design recommendations and best practices, sources for various components,...). Furthermore, this wiki shall also contain general information regarding the managing of the Cambridge University Unmanned Air Systems Society (\'\'handover documents\'\').\n\nThis wiki differs from [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Five_pillars Wikipedia\'s Principles] in the following aspects:\n* This wiki is \'\'\'not an encyclopedia\'\'\' in the sense that original research may be presented on this wiki and information provided does not have to be verifiable by external sources (though it is good practice to add sources when they can be found).\n* This wiki is not neutrally written. Authors may offer their opinions, especially with regards to recommendations and best practices.\n\n==How to contribute to this Wiki==\nTo edit an existing article, simply click the \'Edit\' tab and make your changes. Though this wiki is configured to allow everybody to edit, it is recommended to create an account. This provides a convenient way of tracking your contributions. This Wiki uses a markup language called \'\'Wiki markup\'\', the same language used for [wikipedia.org Wikipedia]. A convenient cheatsheet for Wiki markup may be found [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wiki_markup_cheatsheet_EN.pdf here].',_binary 'utf-8'),(3,_binary 'Welcome to the CUUASS Wiki!\n\n==Purpose of this Wiki==\nA major problem that many student societies (in particular Engineering societies) face is the fact that members generally don\'t stay longer than four years. This makes it very difficult to conserve knowledge. The purpose of this wiki is for CUUASS\'s members (and anybody else who is interested in developing and manufacturing autonomous drones for that matter) to document their knowledge (e.g. manufacturing techniques, usage of various non-self-explanatory tools, documentation of algorithms, design recommendations and best practices, sources for various components,...). Furthermore, this wiki shall also contain general information regarding the managing of the Cambridge University Unmanned Air Systems Society (\'\'handover documents\'\').\n\nThis wiki differs from [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Five_pillars Wikipedia\'s Principles] in the following aspects:\n* This wiki is \'\'\'not an encyclopedia\'\'\' in the sense that original research may be presented on this wiki and information provided does not have to be verifiable by external sources (though it is good practice to add sources when they can be found).\n* This wiki is not neutrally written. Authors may offer their opinions, especially with regards to recommendations and best practices.\n\n==How to contribute to this Wiki==\nTo edit an existing article, simply click the \'Edit\' tab and make your changes. Though this wiki is configured to allow everybody to edit, it is recommended to create an account. This provides a convenient way of tracking your contributions. This Wiki uses a [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markup_language markup language] called \'\'Wiki markup\'\', the same language used for [wikipedia.org Wikipedia]. A convenient cheatsheet for Wiki markup may be found [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wiki_markup_cheatsheet_EN.pdf here].',_binary 'utf-8'),(4,_binary '/* CSS placed here will be applied to all skins */\n\n@media (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 8.1), (min--moz-device-pixel-ratio: 8.1), (min-resolution: 8.1dppx), (min-resolution: 778dpi)\n	#p-logo a {\n		background-image: url(/wiki/logo.png);\n	}\n}',_binary 'utf-8'),(5,_binary '/* CSS placed here will be applied to all skins */',_binary 'utf-8'),(6,_binary 'Welcome to the CUUASS Wiki!\n\n==Purpose of this Wiki==\nA major problem that many student societies (in particular Engineering societies) face is the fact that members generally don\'t stay longer than four years. This makes it very difficult to conserve knowledge. The purpose of this wiki is for CUUASS\'s members (and anybody else who is interested in developing and manufacturing autonomous drones for that matter) to document their knowledge (e.g. manufacturing techniques, usage of various non-self-explanatory tools, documentation of algorithms, design recommendations and best practices, sources for various components,...). Furthermore, this wiki shall also contain general information regarding the managing of the Cambridge University Unmanned Air Systems Society (\'\'handover documents\'\').\n\nThis wiki differs from [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Five_pillars Wikipedia\'s Principles] in the following aspects:\n* This wiki is \'\'\'not an encyclopedia\'\'\' in the sense that original research may be presented on this wiki and information provided does not have to be verifiable by external sources (though it is good practice to add sources when they can be found).\n* This wiki is not neutrally written. Authors may offer their opinions, especially with regards to recommendations and best practices.\n\n==How to contribute to this Wiki==\nTo edit an existing article, simply click the \'Edit\' tab and make your changes. Though this wiki is configured to allow everybody to edit, it is recommended to create an account. This provides a convenient way of tracking your contributions. This Wiki uses a [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markup_language markup language] called \'\'Wiki markup\'\', the same language used for [wikipedia.org Wikipedia]. A convenient cheatsheet for Wiki markup may be found [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wiki_markup_cheatsheet_EN.pdf here]. To create a page that doesn\'t exist yet, enter the title of the article in the search bar at the top. If an article with that title does not exist yet, you will be given the option to create the article.',_binary 'utf-8'),(7,_binary 'Welcome to the CUUASS Wiki!\n\n==Purpose of this Wiki==\nA major problem that many student societies (in particular Engineering societies) face is the fact that members generally don\'t stay longer than four years. This makes it very difficult to conserve knowledge. The purpose of this wiki is for CUUASS\'s members (and anybody else who is interested in developing and manufacturing autonomous drones for that matter) to document their knowledge (e.g. manufacturing techniques, usage of various non-self-explanatory tools, documentation of algorithms, design recommendations and best practices, sources for various components,...). Furthermore, this wiki shall also contain general information regarding the managing of the Cambridge University Unmanned Air Systems Society (\'\'handover documents\'\').\n\nThis wiki differs from [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Five_pillars Wikipedia\'s Principles] in the following aspects:\n* This wiki is \'\'\'not an encyclopedia\'\'\' in the sense that original research may be presented on this wiki and information provided does not have to be verifiable by external sources (though it is good practice to add sources when they can be found).\n* This wiki is not neutrally written. Authors may offer their opinions, especially with regards to recommendations and best practices.\n\n==How to contribute to this Wiki==\nTo edit an existing article, simply click the \'Edit\' tab and make your changes. Though this wiki is configured to allow everybody to edit, it is recommended to create an account. This provides a convenient way of tracking your contributions. This Wiki uses a [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markup_language markup language] called \'\'Wiki markup\'\', the same language used for [https://en.wikipedia.org Wikipedia]. A convenient cheatsheet for Wiki markup may be found [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wiki_markup_cheatsheet_EN.pdf here]. To create a page that doesn\'t exist yet, enter the title of the article in the search bar at the top. If an article with that title does not exist yet, you will be given the option to create the article.',_binary 'utf-8'),(8,_binary 'Personal site: http://philsal.co.uk',_binary 'utf-8'),(9,_binary 'If no dedicated SysAdmin was elected then the President is responsible for the tasks detailed on this site. Ideally a SysAdmin should have some knowledge of the Linux command line, though there is nothing that can\'t be learned. Check out [http://www.linuxcommand.org/tlcl.php this free book] (free in all senses of the word), which should answer most of your questions. This article assumes that you are running Linux, if Linux is not normally your operating system of choice consider installing a Virtual Machine.\n\n\n=Maintaining the website=\n\n==Setting up a local development environment==\n\nIt is recommended to test changes to the website in a local development environment first before you upload them to the website (although this might not be necessary for small changes). To set up such an environment, you need to first install a web server. [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server This guide]  explains the installation procedure for Arch Linux, though it shouldn\'t be much different for other distributions (except perhaps the package names). Be sure to follow the [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server#Configuration Configuration] section. If you keep getting an <code>Error 403</code>, you may solve the problem by running the server as your own user (by changing <code>User yourUserName</code> in <code>httpd.conf</code>, though this is probably not particularly secure. Clone the website from our [https://github.com/CUUASS/WebsitePlusWiki Github repo], and point to it in <code>httpd.conf</code>. Be sure to follow the installation guide for [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server#PHP PHP], otherwise the website won\'t work. If you are particularly ambitious you can also instal [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/MySQL MySQL], which, if you are successful, should allow you to also run the wiki on your computer. Once you are done, simply type <code>localhost</code> in the address bar in your browser and our website should come up.',_binary 'utf-8'),(10,_binary 'If no dedicated SysAdmin was elected then the President is responsible for the tasks detailed on this site. Ideally a SysAdmin should have some knowledge of the Linux command line, though there is nothing that can\'t be learned. Check out [http://www.linuxcommand.org/tlcl.php this free book] (free in all senses of the word), which should answer most of your questions. This article assumes that you are running Linux, if Linux is not normally your operating system of choice consider installing a Virtual Machine.\n\n\n=Maintaining the website (without the Wiki)=\n==Setting up a local development environment==\nIt is recommended to test changes to the website in a local development environment first before you upload them to the website (although this might not be necessary for small changes). To set up such an environment, you need to first install a web server. [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server This guide]  explains the installation procedure for Arch Linux, though it shouldn\'t be much different for other distributions (except perhaps the package names). Be sure to follow the [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server#Configuration Configuration] section. If you keep getting an <code>Error 403</code>, you may solve the problem by running the server as your own user (by changing <code>User yourUserName</code> in <code>httpd.conf</code>, though this is probably not particularly secure. Clone the website from our [https://github.com/CUUASS/WebsitePlusWiki Github repo], and point to it in <code>httpd.conf</code>. Be sure to follow the installation guide for [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server#PHP PHP], otherwise the website won\'t work. If you are particularly ambitious you can also instal [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/MySQL MySQL], which, if you are successful, should allow you to also run the wiki on your computer. Once you are done, simply type <code>localhost</code> in the address bar in your browser and our website should come up.\n\n==Web technologies used==\nThe website uses [https://www.w3schools.com/html/ HTML], [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/PHP PHP], a server-side scripting language, and [https://www.w3schools.com/js/default.asp JavaScript] (a browser-side scripting language). A basic knowledge of HTML will be necessary to make changes to the website. The website uses [https://www.w3schools.com/w3css/ w3.css], a [https://www.w3schools.com/css/default.asp CSS] file that makes styling of the website relatively easy.\n\n==Adding pages and slideshow images==\n\nThe PHP script [https://github.com/CUUASS/WebsitePlusWiki/blob/master/scripts/navigation.php navigation.php] dynamically generates the navigation bar at the top of the website. To add a page, simply navigate to <code>/pages/</code> and make a copy of <code>template.php</code>:\n\n<code>\ncp template.php my_new_page.php\n</code>\n\nEdit the .php file and once you\'re done add an entry in <code>pages.csv</code> since this is the file parsed by <code>navigation.php</code> to create the navigation bar. You will then be able to navigate to the page by clicking in the navgitation bar.\n\nTo add slideshow images, go to <code>/images/slideshow</code>. Note that slideshow images (the images that appear on our [www.cuuass.org homepage]) must be of aspect ratio 3:1. The resolution should be as large as possible (but anything larger than 2560x853 px seems unreasonably large) so that the images look good even on large screens. Furthermore, file size should be limited to 300KB so that the page loads reasonably fast. To achieve this, use your favourite image manipulation program and reduce the jpg quality in the export options until the desired filesize is achieved.\n\n==Connecting to the SRCF server==\n\nYou can connect to the [https://www.srcf.net/ SRCF] server (the server on which our website runs) by typing in a terminal\n\n<code>ssh CRSid@shell.srcf.net</code>\n\nAfter typing in your password, this will bring you to your home directory (<code>/home/CRSid</code>). In your home directory you will find a [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbolic_link symbolic link] that points to the location of the society web root. It is recommended to navigate there not through the symbolic link, otherwise [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Command-line_completion shell completion] might not work properly. This is done by typing\n\n<code>cd /public/societies/cuuass/public_html/</code>\n\n==Uploading/Downloading files to the SRCF server==\n\nYou can upload files using <code>scp</code> (secure copy). Just type\n\n<code>scp fileToBeUploaded CRSid@shell.srcf.net:/public/societies/cuuass/destination</code>\n\nand enter your password.\n\n==File Permissions==\n\n\n=Maintaining the Wiki=',_binary 'utf-8'),(11,_binary 'If no dedicated SysAdmin was elected then the President is responsible for the tasks detailed on this site. Ideally a SysAdmin should have some knowledge of the Linux command line, though there is nothing that can\'t be learned. Check out [http://www.linuxcommand.org/tlcl.php this free book] (free in all senses of the word), which should answer most of your questions. This article assumes that you are running Linux, if Linux is not normally your operating system of choice consider installing a Virtual Machine.\n\n\n=Maintaining the website (without the Wiki)=\n==Setting up a local development environment==\nIt is recommended to test changes to the website in a local development environment first before you upload them to the website (although this might not be necessary for small changes). To set up such an environment, you need to first install a web server. [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server This guide]  explains the installation procedure for Arch Linux, though it shouldn\'t be much different for other distributions (except perhaps the package names). Be sure to follow the [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server#Configuration Configuration] section. If you keep getting an <code>Error 403</code>, you may solve the problem by running the server as your own user (by changing <code>User yourUserName</code> in <code>httpd.conf</code>, though this is probably not particularly secure. Clone the website from our [https://github.com/CUUASS/WebsitePlusWiki Github repo], and point to it in <code>httpd.conf</code>. Be sure to follow the installation guide for [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server#PHP PHP], otherwise the website won\'t work. If you are particularly ambitious you can also instal [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/MySQL MySQL], which, if you are successful, should allow you to also run the wiki on your computer. Once you are done, simply type <code>localhost</code> in the address bar in your browser and our website should come up.\n\n==Web technologies used==\nThe website uses [https://www.w3schools.com/html/ HTML], [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/PHP PHP], a server-side scripting language, and [https://www.w3schools.com/js/default.asp JavaScript] (a browser-side scripting language). A basic knowledge of HTML will be necessary to make changes to the website. The website uses [https://www.w3schools.com/w3css/ w3.css], a [https://www.w3schools.com/css/default.asp CSS] file that makes styling of the website relatively easy.\n\n==Adding pages and slideshow images==\n\nThe PHP script [https://github.com/CUUASS/WebsitePlusWiki/blob/master/scripts/navigation.php navigation.php] dynamically generates the navigation bar at the top of the website. To add a page, simply navigate to <code>/pages/</code> and make a copy of <code>template.php</code>:\n\n<code>\ncp template.php my_new_page.php\n</code>\n\nEdit the .php file and once you\'re done add an entry in <code>pages.csv</code> since this is the file parsed by <code>navigation.php</code> to create the navigation bar. You will then be able to navigate to the page by clicking in the navgitation bar.\n\nTo add slideshow images, go to <code>/images/slideshow</code>. Note that slideshow images (the images that appear on our [www.cuuass.org homepage]) must be of aspect ratio 3:1. The resolution should be as large as possible (but anything larger than 2560x853 px seems unreasonably large) so that the images look good even on large screens. Furthermore, file size should be limited to 300KB so that the page loads reasonably fast. To achieve this, use your favourite image manipulation program and reduce the jpg quality in the export options until the desired filesize is achieved.\n\n==Connecting to the SRCF server==\n\nYou can connect to the [https://www.srcf.net/ SRCF] server (the server on which our website runs) by typing in a terminal\n\n<code>ssh CRSid@shell.srcf.net</code>\n\nAfter typing in your password, this will bring you to your home directory (<code>/home/CRSid</code>). In your home directory you will find a [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbolic_link symbolic link] that points to the location of the society web root. It is recommended to navigate there not through the symbolic link, otherwise [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Command-line_completion shell completion] might not work properly. This is done by typing\n\n<code>cd /public/societies/cuuass/public_html/</code>\n\n==Uploading/Downloading files to the SRCF server==\n\nYou can upload files using <code>scp</code> (secure copy). Just type\n\n<code>scp fileToBeUploaded CRSid@shell.srcf.net:/public/societies/cuuass/destination</code>\n\nand enter your password. After uploading, be sure to set the correct file permissions (see next section)!\n\n==File Permissions==\nAfter uploading files to the server you should make sure that the correct file permissions are set. If you don\'t know about Linux file permissions, check out the permissions chapter in [http://www.linuxcommand.org/tlcl.php The Linux Command Line]. For regular files, reasonable permissions are 660. Every cuuass administrator is part of the cuuass group and files should be writable for everybody, thus group write permissions are recommended. To se the correct permissions, the kind people at SRFC have written a bash script that does just that. To execute this script, simply type <code>srcf-soc-permfix cuuass</code>. The script does the following:\n* finds files in <code>/public/societies/$socname</code> that do not belong to the group <code>$socname</code> and changes their group to <code>$socname</code>,\n* finds files in <code>/public/societies/$socname</code> which do not have group read and write permissions and adds those permissions,\n* finds directories in <code>/public/societies/$socname</code> that do not have the setgid bit set and sets the setgid bit.\nIf something is working fine on your local machine but not on the server, chances are that the permissions are wrong. It is recommended to always run the SRCF\'s script after uploading something to the server via <code>scp</code>.\n\n=FAQ=\nBe sure to check out the [ SRCF\'s FAQ].\n\n=Maintaining the Wiki=',_binary 'utf-8'),(12,_binary 'If no dedicated SysAdmin was elected then the President is responsible for the tasks detailed on this site. Ideally a SysAdmin should have some knowledge of the Linux command line, though there is nothing that can\'t be learned. Check out [http://www.linuxcommand.org/tlcl.php this free book] (free in all senses of the word), which should answer most of your questions. This article assumes that you are running Linux, if Linux is not normally your operating system of choice consider installing a Virtual Machine.\n\n\n=Maintaining the website (without the Wiki)=\n==Setting up a local development environment==\nIt is recommended to test changes to the website in a local development environment first before you upload them to the website (although this might not be necessary for small changes). To set up such an environment, you need to first install a web server. [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server This guide]  explains the installation procedure for Arch Linux, though it shouldn\'t be much different for other distributions (except perhaps the package names). Be sure to follow the [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server#Configuration Configuration] section. If you keep getting an <code>Error 403</code>, you may solve the problem by running the server as your own user (by changing <code>User yourUserName</code> in <code>httpd.conf</code>, though this is probably not particularly secure. Clone the website from our [https://github.com/CUUASS/WebsitePlusWiki Github repo], and point to it in <code>httpd.conf</code>.