 page loads reasonably fast. To achieve this, use your favourite image manipulation program and reduce the jpg quality in the export options until the desired filesize is achieved.\n\n==Connecting to the SRCF server==\n\nYou can connect to the [https://www.srcf.net/ SRCF] server (the server on which our website runs) by typing in a terminal\n\n<code>ssh CRSid@shell.srcf.net</code>\n\nAfter typing in your password, this will bring you to your home directory (<code>/home/CRSid</code>). In your home directory you will find a [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbolic_link symbolic link] that points to the location of the society web root. It is recommended to navigate there not through the symbolic link, otherwise [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Command-line_completion shell completion] might not work properly. This is done by typing\n\n<code>cd /public/societies/cuuass/public_html/</code>\n\n==Uploading/Downloading files to the SRCF server==\n\nYou can upload files using <code>scp</code> (secure copy). Just type\n\n<code>scp fileToBeUploaded CRSid@shell.srcf.net:/public/societies/cuuass/destination</code>\n\nand enter your password. After uploading, be sure to set the correct file permissions (see next section)!\n\n==File Permissions==\nAfter uploading files to the server you should make sure that the correct file permissions are set. If you don\'t know about Linux file permissions, check out the permissions chapter in [http://www.linuxcommand.org/tlcl.php The Linux Command Line]. For regular files, reasonable permissions are 660. Every cuuass administrator is part of the cuuass group and files should be writable for everybody, thus group write permissions are recommended. To se the correct permissions, the kind people at SRFC have written a bash script that does just that. To execute this script, simply type <code>srcf-soc-permfix cuuass</code>. The script does the following:\n* finds files in <code>/public/societies/$socname</code> that do not belong to the group <code>$socname</code> and changes their group to <code>$socname</code>,\n* finds files in <code>/public/societies/$socname</code> which do not have group read and write permissions and adds those permissions,\n* finds directories in <code>/public/societies/$socname</code> that do not have the setgid bit set and sets the setgid bit.\nIf something is working fine on your local machine but not on the server, chances are that the permissions are wrong. It is recommended to always run the SRCF\'s script after uploading something to the server via <code>scp</code>.\n\n=FAQ=\nBe sure to check out the [https://www.srcf.net/faq/ SRCF\'s FAQ].\n\n=Maintaining the Wiki=',_binary 'utf-8'),(13,_binary 'If no dedicated SysAdmin was elected then the President is responsible for the tasks detailed on this site. Ideally a SysAdmin should have some knowledge of the Linux command line, though there is nothing that can\'t be learned. Check out [http://www.linuxcommand.org/tlcl.php this free book] (free in all senses of the word), which should answer most of your questions. This article assumes that you are running Linux, if Linux is not normally your operating system of choice consider installing a Virtual Machine.\n\n\n=Maintaining the website (without the Wiki)=\n==Setting up a local development environment==\nIt is recommended to test changes to the website in a local development environment first before you upload them to the website (although this might not be necessary for small changes). To set up such an environment, you need to first install a web server. [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server This guide]  explains the installation procedure for Arch Linux, though it shouldn\'t be much different for other distributions (except perhaps the package names). Be sure to follow the [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server#Configuration Configuration] section. If you keep getting an <code>Error 403</code>, you may solve the problem by running the server as