eople at SRFC have written a bash script that does just that. To execute this script, simply type <code>srcf-soc-permfix cuuass</code>. The script does the following:\n* finds files in <code>/public/societies/$socname</code> that do not belong to the group <code>$socname</code> and changes their group to <code>$socname</code>,\n* finds files in <code>/public/societies/$socname</code> which do not have group read and write permissions and adds those permissions,\n* finds directories in <code>/public/societies/$socname</code> that do not have the setgid bit set and sets the setgid bit.\nIf something is working fine on your local machine but not on the server, chances are that the permissions are wrong. It is recommended to always run the SRCF\'s script after uploading something to the server via <code>scp</code>.\n\n=FAQ=\nBe sure to check out the [https://www.srcf.net/faq/ SRCF\'s FAQ].\n\n=Security of the Wiki=\nThis wiki uses [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/MediaWiki MediaWiki], the same software package on which Wikipedia runs. The installation can be found under </code>/wiki/</code>. For this wiki, file uploads are enabled. This poses a potential security risk. To ensure that users cannot do damage by uploading malicious scripts, the upload directory needs to have server-side execution of PHP scripts disabled, see [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:Security#Upload_security here].',_binary 'utf-8'),(14,_binary 'If no dedicated SysAdmin was elected then the President is responsible for the tasks detailed on this site. Ideally a SysAdmin should have some knowledge of the Linux command line, though there is nothing that can\'t be learned. Check out [http://www.linuxcommand.org/tlcl.php this free book] (free in all senses of the word), which should answer most of your questions. This article assumes that you are running Linux, if Linux is not normally your operating system of choice consider installing a Virtual Machine.\n\n\n=Maintaining the Website=\n==Setting u