\";\n        $wgDBserver = \"localhost\";\n        $wgDBuser = \"cuuass\";\n        $wgDBpassword = \"ourSecretMySqlPassword\";\n?>\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThis script **must not be world readable** so that other users of the server cannot see our MySQL password (i.e. permissions 660). Check out [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:Securing_database_passwords this page on MediaWiki on database password security].\n\n==MediaWiki extensions==\nMediaWiki supports several extensions that reside under <code>/wiki/extensions/</code>. To install an extension, follow [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:Extensions this guide]. Currently, this wiki has the extensions [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Extension:SyntaxHighlight SyntaxHighlight_GeSHi] and [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Extension:CategoryTree CategoryTree] installed, as can be seen by examining <code>/wiki/LocalSettings.php</code> (or alternatively see the page [[Special:Version]]).\n\n=Backup and Restore=\n==Backup==\nIt is good practice to keep a backup of the website in case something happens to the web server. There are two parts to such a backup:\n# the files in the webroot directory and\n# the contents of our MySQL database.\nFor this purpose, the user <code>rnw29</code> wrote a simple bash script following [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:Backing_up_a_wiki#Database this guide] to create a backup and upload it to our [https://github.com/CUUASS/WebsitePlusWiki GitHub repo]. This script resides under <code>/public/societies/cuuass/scripts/</code>:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\n#!/bin/bash\n\n# first create Database dump\necho \'$wgReadOnly = \"Dumping Database, Access will be restored shortly\"\' \\\n        >> /public/societies/cuuass/public_html/wiki/LocalSettings.php\n\n# nice -n 19 lowers the priority of the process\nnice -n 19 mysqldump -h localhost -u cuuass -p --default-character-set=binary cuuass \\\n     --password=\"outSecretMySqlPassword\" \\\n        > /public/societies/cuuass/public_html/wiki_backup/backup.sql\n\n# remove last line from LocalSettings.php which was added above\n# thus restoring write access to wiki\nsed -i \'$ d\' /public/societies/cuuass/public_html/wiki/LocalSettings.php\n\n# Now do a git commit and push to github\ncd /public/societies/cuuass/public_html/\nnice -n 19 git add -A\ngit commit -m \"This is an automatic commit, created on $(date)\"\ngit push\necho \"done\"\ncd -\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nAgain, this script must have permissions 660 so the password is not world-readable. The user <code>rnw29</code> installed a [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cron cronjob] for this script that runs every Monday at 4:30am. It is worth checking the [https://github.com/CUUASS/WebsitePlusWiki GitHub repo] to see if commits are actually being made on a weekly basis. If not, suspicion should arise!\n\nYou might be worried that the SQL dump also contains passwords of wiki users, however these passwords are [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographic_hash_function hashed] using a [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salt_(cryptography) random salt], which would make it difficult for an attacker to find out the passwords.\n\n==Restore==\nTo restore the website in case of corruption, simply clone the [https://github.com/CUUASS/WebsitePlusWiki Github repo]. To restore the MySQL database, follow [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:Restoring_a_wiki_from_backup these instructions].',_binary 'utf-8'),(29,_binary '[[Category:Committee]]\n\nIf no dedicated SysAdmin was elected then the President is responsible for the tasks detailed on this site. Ideally a SysAdmin should have some knowledge of the Linux command line, though there is nothing that can\'t be learned. Check out [http://www.linuxcommand.org/tlcl.php this free book] (free in all senses of the word), which should answer most of your questions. This article assumes that you are running Linux, if Linux is not normally your operating system of choice consider installing a Virtual Machine.\n\n\n=Maintaining the Website=\n==Setting up a local development environment==\nIt is recommended to test changes to the website in a local development environment first before you upload them to the website (although this might not be necessary for small changes). To set up such an environment, you need to first install a web server. [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server This guide]  explains the installation procedure for Arch Linux, though it shouldn\'t be much different for other distributions (except perhaps the package names). Be sure to follow the [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server#Configuration Configuration] section. If you keep getting an <code>Error 403</code>, you may solve the problem by running the server as your own user (by changing <code>User yourUserName</code> in <code>httpd.conf</code>, though this is probably not particularly secure. Clone the website from our [https://github.com/CUUASS/WebsitePlusWiki Github repo], and point to it in <code>httpd.conf</code>. Be sure to follow the installation guide for [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Apache_HTTP_Server#PHP PHP], otherwise the website won\'t work. If you are particularly ambitious you can also instal [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/MySQL MySQL], which, if you are successful, should allow you to also run the wiki on your computer. Once you are done, simply type <code>localhost</code> in the address bar in your browser and our website should come up.\n\n==Web technologies used==\nThe website uses [https://www.w3schools.com/html/ HTML], [https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/PHP PHP], a server-side scripting language, and [https://www.w3schools.com/js/default.asp JavaScript] (a browser-side scripting language). A basic knowledge of HTML will be necessary to make changes to the website. The website uses [https://www.w3schools.com/w3css/ w3.css], a [https://www.w3schools.com/css/default.asp CSS] file that makes styling of the website relatively easy.\n\n==Adding pages and slideshow images==\n\nThe PHP script [https://github.com/CUUASS/WebsitePlusWiki/blob/master/scripts/navigation.php navigation.php] dynamically generates the navigation bar at the top of the website. To add a page, simply navigate to <code>/pages/</code> and make a copy of <code>template.php</code>:\n\n<code>\ncp template.php my_new_page.php\n</code>\n\nEdit the .php file and once you\'re done add an entry in <code>pages.csv</code> since this is the file parsed by <code>navigation.php</code> to create the navigation bar. You will then be able to navigate to the page by clicking in the navgitation bar.\n\nTo add slideshow images, go to <code>/images/slideshow</code>. Note that slideshow images (the images that appear on our [www.cuuass.org homepage]) must be of aspect ratio 3:1. The resolution should be as large as possible (but anything larger than 2560x853 px seems unreasonably large) so that the images look good even on large screens. Furthermore, file size should be limited to 300KB so that the page loads reasonably fast. To achieve this, use your favourite image manipulation program and reduce the jpg quality in the export options until the desired filesize is achieved.\n\n==Connecting to the SRCF server==\n\nYou can connect to the [https://www.srcf.net/ SRCF] server (the server on which our website runs) by typing in a terminal\n\n<code>ssh CRSid@shell.srcf.net</code>\n\nAfter typing in your password, this will bring you to your home directory (<code>/home/CRSid</code>). In your home directory you will find a [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbolic_link symbolic link] that points to the location of the society web root. It is recommended to navigate there not through the symbolic link, otherwise [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Command-line_completion shell completion] might not work properly. This is done by typing\n\n<code>cd /public/societies/cuuass/public_html/</code>\n\n==Uploading/Downloading files to the SRCF server==\n\nYou can upload file